<worksheet>
  <title>Proof Practice</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      <alert>Foundations of Mathematics</alert>
    </p>
  </introduction>


	<p>
		First, let’s look at the formal proof that when <m>x\in {\bf Z}</m>, <m>x</m> is even if and only if <m>x</m> is not odd. First, a reminder of the Division Algorithm (misnamed, because it’s a theorem—or if you’re in a rush, an axiom—and not an algorithm):
	</p>

	<p>
		<term>Division Algorithm</term>. Suppose <m>a\in{\bf Z}</m> and <m>b\in{\bf Z}^+</m>. Then there exist unique integers <m>q</m> and <m>r</m> such that <m>a = bq + r</m> and <m>0\leq r &lt; b</m>.
	</p>

	<p>
		<term>Proposition</term>. Suppose <m>x\in{\bf Z}</m>. Then <m>x</m> is even or <m>x</m> is odd, and <m>x</m> is not both even and odd.
	</p>

	<p>
		<term>Proof.</term> Let <m>x</m> be an integer. By the Division Algorithm, there exist unique integers <m>q</m> and <m>r</m> such that <m>x = 2q + r</m> and <m>0\leq r &lt; 2</m>. Note that this means that either <m>r = 0</m> or <m>r = 1</m>.
	</p>

	<p>
		<em>Case 1: r = 0.</em>
	</p>

	<p>
		In this case, <m>x = 2q + 0 = 2q</m> and <m>q</m> is an integer, so by definition <m>x</m> is even. Moreover, if <m>x</m> were odd, then there would exist an integer <m>k</m> such that <m>x = 2k + 1</m>, which would mean that <m>r = 0</m> is not unique. Thus, <m>x</m> is not odd.
	</p>

	<p>
		<em>Case 2: r = 1.</em>
	</p>

	<p>
		In this case, <m>x = 2q + 1</m> and <m>q</m> is an integer, so by definition <m>x</m> is odd. Moreover, if <m>x</m> were even, then there would exist an integer <m>k</m> such that <m>x = 2k = 2k + 0</m>, which would mean that <m>r = 1</m> is not unique. Thus, <m>x</m> is not even.
	</p>

	<p>
		In both possible cases, <m>x</m> is even or odd but not both. <m>\square</m>
	</p>

	<p>
		So, just to reaffirm: you may freely use the fact that when <m>x</m> is an integer, if <m>x</m> is not even then <m>x</m> is odd, and if <m>x</m> is not odd than <m>x</m> is even.
	</p>

	<p>
		Now, some proofs for you to try. Some of them will use the following definition (implicit in our description of <m>{\bf Q}</m> in Chapter 1):
	</p>

	<p>
		<term>Definition.</term> Suppose <m>x\in{\bf R}</m>. Then <m>x</m> is <term>rational</term> when there exist <m>a,b\in{\bf Z}</m> such that <m>x = a/b</m>. Otherwise, <m>x</m> is <term>irrational</term>.
	</p>

	<p><ol>
		<li>
			<p>
				Suppose <m>a,b,c\in{\bf Z}</m>. Prove that if <m>c|a</m> and <m>c|b</m>, then <m>c^2|(a^2 - ab + b^2)</m>.
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<p>
				Suppose that <m>x,y\in{\bf R}</m>.
			</p>
		
			<p>
				Prove that if <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are rational, then <m>x + y</m> is also rational.
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<p>
				Suppose that <m>x,y\in{\bf R}</m> and that <m>x</m> is rational. (In other words, <m>x\in{\bf Q}</m>.)
			</p>
		
			<p>
				Prove that if <m>xy</m> is irrational, then <m>y</m> is irrational.
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<p>
				Suppose <m>n\in{\bf Z}</m>. Prove that if <m>n^2</m> is not divisible by <m>4</m>, then <m>n</m> is odd.
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<p>
				Suppose that <m>k</m> and <m>m</m> are integers. Prove that if <m>k + m</m> is even, then <m>k - m</m> is even.
			</p>
		</li>

	</ol></p>


</worksheet>